==Encoding schemes==
===Unicode===
Equivalents for some (but not all) cirth can be found in the [[Runic (Unicode block)|Runic block]] of Unicode.

Three runic letters invented by Tolkien were added to the block in June 2014, with the release of Unicode 7.0:
<div style="font-family: Quivira, Everson Mono;">
*{{unichar|16F1|RUNIC LETTER K}}
*{{unichar|16F2|RUNIC LETTER SH}}
*{{unichar|16F3|RUNIC LETTER OO}}
</div>

A formal [[Unicode]] proposal to encode Cirth as a separate script was made in September 1997 by [[Michael Everson]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://std.dkuug.dk/JTC1/SC2/WG2/docs/n1642/n1642.htm|title=N1642: Proposal to encode Cirth in Plane 1 of ISO/IEC 10646-2 | first = Michael | last = Everson | publisher=Working Group Document, ISO/IEC JTC1/SC2/WG2 and UTC|date=1997-09-18|accessdate=2015-08-08}}</ref>
No action was taken by the Unicode Technical Committee (UTC) but Cirth appears in the Roadmap to the SMP.<ref name="roadmapsmp">{{cite web|url=https://www.unicode.org/roadmaps/smp/ |title=Roadmap to the SMP |publisher=Unicode.org |date=2015-06-03 |accessdate=2015-08-08}}</ref>

